(44, 7, 20, 2, 2, 2, 10, 'nourished up in his father’s house three months', 'Moses'' Early Life Connection', 'Both passages emphasize Moses'' early life and his nurturing. Acts 7:20 mentions Moses being nourished for three months, paralleling Exodus 2:2, which describes his mother hiding him for the same duration.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 20, 9, 16, 12, 12, 'exceeding fair', 'Physical Beauty of Key Figures', 'This connection highlights the physical beauty of significant biblical figures. Both Moses and David are described as ''exceeding fair'' and ''beautiful countenance,'' suggesting a theme of divine selection based on their appearance.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 21, 58, 11, 24, 24, NULL, 'Moses'' Identity and Choices', 'Both passages emphasize Moses'' relationship with Pharaoh''s daughter. Acts 7:21 notes he was nourished by her, while Hebrews 11:24 highlights his refusal to be called her son, indicating a significant choice in his identity.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 21, 2, 2, 2, 10, 'took him up, and nourished him for her own son', 'Moses'' Adoption by Pharaoh''s Daughter', 'Both passages emphasize the act of Pharaoh''s daughter taking Moses as her own son. This connection highlights the compassion she showed when she found him in the river, leading to his upbringing in the Egyptian royal household.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 21, 5, 32, 26, 26, 'cast out', 'Themes of Abandonment and Preservation', 'This connection highlights the theme of being cast out and yet preserved. In Acts, Moses is abandoned but taken in by Pharaoh’s daughter, while Deuteronomy speaks of scattering and making remembrance cease, suggesting a tension between abandonment and preservation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 22, 23, 19, 11, 11, 'learned in all the wisdom of the Egyptians', 'Wisdom and Counsel of Pharaoh', 'Both passages emphasize the wisdom associated with Egyptian leadership. Acts highlights Moses'' learning in Egyptian wisdom, while Isaiah critiques the foolishness of Pharaoh''s counselors, suggesting a contrast in wisdom.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 22, 14, 9, 22, 22, 'wisdom', 'Wisdom of Leaders', 'Both passages emphasize the wisdom of prominent leaders, with Moses being learned in Egyptian wisdom and Solomon surpassing all kings in wisdom. This connection highlights the significance of wisdom in leadership roles within the biblical narrative.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 22, 27, 1, 4, 4, 'learned in all the wisdom', 'Wisdom and Skill in Leadership', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of wisdom and skill in individuals chosen for leadership roles. Moses is described as learned in the wisdom of the Egyptians, while the children in Daniel are noted for their skill in wisdom and knowledge.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 22, 27, 1, 17, 20, 'wisdom of the Egyptians', 'Wisdom and Understanding in Leaders', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of wisdom and understanding given to prominent figures. Moses is described as ''learned in all the wisdom of the Egyptians,'' while Daniel and his companions are noted for their ''knowledge and skill in all learning and wisdom.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 22, 42, 24, 19, 19, 'mighty in words and in deeds', 'Mighty in Deed and Word', 'This connection highlights the parallel descriptions of Moses and Jesus, both noted for their might in deeds and words. The emphasis on being ''mighty in words and in deeds'' in Acts resonates with Jesus being described as ''mighty in deed and word.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 22, 11, 4, 29, 30, 'wisdom of the Egyptians', 'Wisdom of Egypt Connection', 'Both passages emphasize wisdom associated with Egypt. Acts highlights Moses'' learning in Egyptian wisdom, while 1 Kings describes Solomon''s wisdom exceeding that of Egypt.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 23, 2, 2, 11, 12, 'to visit his brethren', 'Moses'' Compassion for His People', 'This connection highlights Moses'' desire to visit his brethren, which leads to his act of looking on their burdens. Both passages emphasize his growing awareness of the suffering of the children of Israel.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 23, 20, 21, 1, 1, 'came into his heart', 'Divine Influence on Hearts', 'This connection highlights how both passages emphasize the role of God in influencing human hearts. In Acts, Moses'' heart is moved to visit his brethren, while Proverbs illustrates that the Lord directs the king''s heart as He wills.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 23, 58, 11, 24, 26, 'to visit his brethren the children of Israel', 'Moses'' Choice and Identity', 'This connection highlights Moses'' decision to identify with his brethren, as noted in Acts 7:23, and his subsequent refusal of his royal status in Hebrews 11:24. Both passages emphasize his choice to align with the people of God over worldly pleasures.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 23, 15, 7, 27, 27, NULL, 'Divine Inspiration in Action', 'This connection highlights the theme of God placing intentions in the hearts of individuals. Both passages emphasize a pivotal moment where a significant action is inspired by divine influence.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 23, 50, 2, 12, 13, 'to visit his brethren', 'Working Out Salvation Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of taking initiative in one''s spiritual journey. In Acts, Moses decides to visit his brethren, reflecting a personal commitment, while Philippians encourages believers to actively work out their salvation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 23, 59, 1, 17, 17, 'visit his brethren', 'Connection of Gifts and Actions', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine purpose in both passages. Acts 7:23 speaks of Moses'' intention to visit his brethren, while James 1:17 emphasizes that good gifts come from above, suggesting that actions aligned with divine will are inherently good.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 23, 66, 17, 17, 17, 'to visit his brethren', 'Divine Influence on Hearts', 'This connection highlights the theme of God influencing hearts to fulfill His purposes. In Acts, Moses is moved to visit his brethren, while in Revelation, God puts it in their hearts to fulfill His will.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 24, 43, 18, 10, 11, 'smote the Egyptian', 'Defense and Violence in Context', 'This connection highlights the theme of defending the oppressed through violence. Both passages depict acts of aggression in response to perceived injustice, with Moses smiting the Egyptian and Peter cutting off Malchus''s ear.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 24, 43, 18, 25, 27, NULL, 'Denial and Defense Motif', 'This connection highlights the theme of defense and denial. In Acts, Moses defends an oppressed Hebrew, while in John, Peter denies his association with Jesus, contrasting the act of defending with the act of denial.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 24, 44, 7, 28, 28, 'defended him, and avenged him that was oppressed', 'Moses'' Defense of the Oppressed', 'This connection highlights Moses'' action of defending the oppressed in the source verse, which is directly referenced in the target passage when the question of killing arises. Both passages emphasize the theme of Moses'' intervention on behalf of those suffering wrong.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 25, 9, 14, 45, 45, 'understood how that God by his hand would deliver them', 'Understanding God''s Deliverance', 'This connection highlights the theme of misunderstanding God''s deliverance. In Acts, the brethren fail to recognize Moses as their deliverer, while in 1 Samuel, the people acknowledge Jonathan''s role in salvation but initially question his fate.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 25, 9, 19, 5, 5, 'understood how that God by his hand', 'Understanding God''s Deliverance', 'This connection highlights the theme of misunderstanding God''s purpose in deliverance. In Acts, the brethren fail to recognize Moses as their deliverer, while in 1 Samuel, Saul''s intent to harm David contrasts with the recognition of God''s salvation through David''s victory over Goliath.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 25, 12, 5, 1, 1, 'understood how that God by his hand would deliver them', 'Understanding Deliverance Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of deliverance, with Acts 7:25 highlighting the expectation of understanding God''s plan for deliverance, while 2 Kings 5:1 presents Naaman as a recipient of deliverance despite his leprosy. This connection highlights the contrast between perceived and actual understanding of God''s workings.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 25, 19, 106, 7, 7, 'understood not', 'Understanding God''s Deliverance', 'Both passages emphasize a lack of understanding regarding God''s actions. In Acts, Moses'' brethren did not recognize God''s intent for deliverance, paralleling how the fathers in Psalms did not understand God''s wonders in Egypt.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
